Cursor Project Rules — Flutter Personal Finance App
1. Project Overview

This project is a personal finance mobile app designed primarily for Android and optimized for offline use.

The app tracks:

income

expenses

budgets

accounts

transactions

The app supports two currencies used in Zimbabwe:

USD

ZWG

All financial calculations must use USD as the internal base currency.

The application must remain simple, maintainable, and fast to build.

2. Technology Stack

Allowed technologies:

Flutter (latest stable)

Dart

SQLite using sqflite

Riverpod for state management

intl for date formatting

Avoid adding unnecessary dependencies.

Disallowed technologies unless explicitly requested:

Firebase

GraphQL

backend APIs

Clean Architecture frameworks

heavy dependency injection frameworks

Bloc / Redux / MobX

This is an offline-first mobile app.

3. Project Folder Structure

All code must follow this structure:

lib/
  main.dart

  models/
  database/
  services/
  providers/
  screens/
  widgets/
  utils/

Responsibilities:

models/

data classes only

no database code

no UI logic

database/

SQLite initialization

schema creation

migrations

raw queries if needed

services/

business logic

database operations

currency calculations

summaries

providers/

Riverpod providers

state management

screens/

full app pages

widgets/

reusable UI components

utils/

helper functions

formatters

constants

4. State Management Rules

Use Riverpod.

Rules:

UI must never access SQLite directly

UI interacts only with providers

providers call services

services interact with the database

Flow must always be:

UI Screen
   ↓
Provider
   ↓
Service
   ↓
Database

Avoid:

database queries in widgets

business logic in UI

5. Widget Design Rules

Prefer StatelessWidget.

Use ConsumerWidget when reading providers.

Avoid large widgets.

If a widget exceeds ~150 lines, split it into smaller widgets.

Widgets must follow this order:

constructor

fields

build method

private helper widgets

6. Performance Rules

Avoid unnecessary rebuilds.

Guidelines:

Use ref.watch() only where needed

Use ref.read() for actions

Split UI widgets to minimize rebuilds

Large lists must use:

ListView.builder

Never use large static ListView widgets for dynamic data.

7. Database Design Rules

Database: SQLite using sqflite

Tables must be minimal.

Required tables:

accounts

id
name
currency
balance
created_at

transactions

id
account_id
type
category
amount
currency
exchange_rate_to_usd
amount_in_usd
date
note
created_at

budgets

id
category
amount
currency
month
year

categories

id
name
type
8. Currency Handling Rules

The system supports:

USD

ZWG

All internal calculations must convert values to USD.

Every transaction must store:

amount
currency
exchange_rate_to_usd
amount_in_usd

Exchange rates are entered manually by the user.

Historical transactions must never be recalculated.

9. Database Performance Rules

All transaction queries must support filtering by:

date

category

account

Transactions must be indexed by:

date

account_id

Example SQL index:

CREATE INDEX idx_transactions_date
ON transactions(date);

Large transaction lists must use pagination.

10. Error Handling Rules

Database calls must use try/catch.

Errors must not crash the UI.

Services should return:

valid data

or controlled error responses

Avoid exposing raw exceptions to UI.

11. Code Style Rules

All Dart code must follow:

null safety

clear variable names

small functions

early returns instead of nested conditions

Avoid functions longer than ~40 lines.

Avoid files longer than ~300 lines.

12. Data Entry UX Rules

Finance apps prioritize speed of entry.

Important screens must minimize taps.

Primary screens:

Dashboard

Add Transaction

Transactions List

Budgets

Accounts

"Add Transaction" must be the fastest action in the app.

13. Chart and Summary Rules

Summary calculations should happen in services, not UI.

Examples:

monthly spending

category totals

income vs expense

savings rate

UI should only display computed results.

14. Logging Rules

Use simple logging for development.

Do not introduce full logging frameworks yet.

Use:

debugPrint()

for debugging.

15. Future Proofing

Design the app so it can later support:

cloud sync

user accounts

backend APIs

But do not implement those features now.

Avoid premature abstraction.

16. Development Philosophy

This project prioritizes:

simplicity

speed of development

maintainability

offline reliability

Avoid overengineering.

The goal is to ship a working Android app quickly.
